Mountain Peak

You are given a list of integers heightsheights representing the heights of NN mountain peaks. 
For each peak, you need to find the height of the next higher peak that comes after it in the list. 
If there is no higher peak after a given peak, return −1−1 for that peak.
Input Format
    The first line contains one integer nn, the size of the list of integers. - Next line contains nn integers heights[0],heights[1]...heights[n]heights[0],heights[1]...heights[n], representing the peaks .

Output Format
    For each peak, print the next higher peak that comes after it in the list. If there is no higher peak for a peak than print −1−1.

Constraints
    1≤n≤1000001≤n≤100000
    0≤heights[i]≤10000000≤heights[i]≤1000000

Sample 1:
Input
2
1 2
Output
2 -1
Explanation:
The next greater element for 1 is 2 and for 2 there is no next greater element so for 2 it will be -1.
Sample 2:
Input
4
6 5 3 6
Output
-1 6 6 -1
Explanation:
For the first 6 there is no element greater than 6 on its right so the peak for the first 6 is -1. For 5 , 6 is the next peak as it is on the right side and is greater than 5. 
For the next element 3 , 6 is the peak as it is on the right side and is greater than 3, for the last 6 , no peak is there on the right side so -1 is there.
*/

import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static int[] nextHigherPeak(int[] heights) {
        int n = heights.length;
        int[] result = new int[n];

        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            while (!stack.isEmpty() && stack.peek() <= heights[i]) {
                stack.pop();
            }

            if (stack.isEmpty()) {
                result[i] = -1;
            } else {
                result[i] = stack.peek();
            }

            stack.push(heights[i]);
        }

        return result;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        int[] heights = new int[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            heights[i] = sc.nextInt();
        }

        int[] result = nextHigherPeak(heights);

        for (int height : result) {
            System.out.print(height + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
